Problem 1: Use polynomials and ridge regression to predict stock returns

This problem uses the built in EuStockMarkets dataset. The dataset contains time series of closing prices of major European stock indices from 1991 to 1998. We use only the FTSE column in this problem. The dataset is a time series object, but you will need to extract the FTSE column and make it into a data frame.

data("EuStockMarkets")
FTSE <- EuStockMarkets[,4]
Time <- as.numeric(time(EuStockMarkets))
df <- data.frame(Time, FTSE)

part a: Fit polynomial models of degrees 4, 8, 12 to the FTSE data and plot all three fitted curves together with a scatterplot of the data. Comment on the plots. Which features in the data are resolved by the polynomial models? Which features are not resolved? Do the polynomial curves show any artifacts such as oscillations?

degree4 <- lm(FTSE~poly(Time, 4), data = df)
degree8 <- lm(FTSE~poly(Time, 8), data = df)
degree12 <- lm(FTSE~poly(Time, 12), data = df)
pred1 <- predict(degree4)
pred2 <- predict(degree8)
pred3 <- predict(degree12)
library(ggplot2)

ggplot(data = df, aes(x=Time, y=FTSE)) + 
  geom_point(lwd=0.3, color="darkgrey") +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', formula = y~poly(x, 4), color = "red") + 
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', formula = y~poly(x, 8), color = 'orange')+

library(glmnet)

library(gam)

gam5 <- gam(Sales~ s(TV, 5) + s(Radio, 5) + s(Newspaper, 5) , data=ad)
gam6 <- gam(Sales~ s(TV, 6) + s(Radio, 6) + s(Newspaper, 6) , data=ad)
# compare rms prediction errors to the rms prediction error of a multiple regression model
#on the training set
r=rmse(train.data$Sales, predict(lm, train.data))

r4=rmse(train.data$Sales, predict(gam4, train.data))
r5=rmse(train.data$Sales, predict(gam5, train.data))
r6=rmse(train.data$Sales, predict(gam6, train.data))

##          r       r2       r3       r4       r5       r6

R4=rmse(test.data$Sales, predict(gam4, test.data))
R5=rmse(test.data$Sales, predict(gam5, test.data))

part b: Is there evidence of overfitting?

No. The train rmse is higher than the test rmse.

part c: You now have six models (five GAM and one LM). Which model should be used? Explain your answer.

The GAM with smoothing spline degree of 6 should be used, because it has the lowest test rmse.

Problem 5: Compare the characteristics of two different smoothing splines

part a:
The g hat 2 will have smaller RSS. Because as λ→∞, the penalty term will become more important. So, g hat 1 will be the quadratic that minimizes the training RSS and g hat 2 will be a will be the cubic that minimizes the training RSS. g hat 2 will be more flexible so it has smaller training RSS.

part b: It is hard to tell because the relationship between x and y is unknown.

part c: The penalty term can be ignored when lambda = 0. The g hat 1 and g hat 2 will have the same training and test RSS.

Problem 6: Explain the behavior of the curve for a variety of λ and m values.

Use the following starter code to make your set of points and plot your various model predictions.

set.seed(325626)
X <- runif(100)
eps <- rnorm(100)
Y <- sin(12*(X + 0.2)) / (X + 0.2) + eps
generating_fn <- function(X) {sin(12*(X + 0.2)) / (X + 0.2)} 
df <- data.frame(X, Y)

ggplot(df, aes(x = X, y = Y)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +

  1. \(λ=∞,m=0\)
